### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe the problem.

Yes, the problem is that the current email confirmation flow is entirely managed by the backend, which sends an email directly to the user with a confirmation link. This approach creates a tight coupling between the backend and client side. It limits the flexibility of the client to control the user experience and slows down the iteration process for making changes to the confirmation UI.

For example, if we need to change the UI or process for confirming email addresses, we would need to modify the backend logic and redeploy it, rather than just making changes on the client. This creates unnecessary overhead for front-end developers and leads to a more monolithic approach.

Additionally, this method does not provide a streamlined way for the client to handle the entire flow (e.g., validating and displaying messages), which is increasingly common in modern web applications that separate concerns between client side and backend.

```csharp
async Task SendConfirmationEmailAsync(TUser user, UserManager<TUser> userManager, HttpContext context, string email, bool isChange = false)
{
    if (confirmEmailEndpointName is null)
    {
        throw new NotSupportedException("No email confirmation endpoint was registered!");
    }

    var code = isChange
        ? await userManager.GenerateChangeEmailTokenAsync(user, email)
        : await userManager.GenerateEmailConfirmationTokenAsync(user);
    code = WebEncoders.Base64UrlEncode(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(code));

    var userId = await userManager.GetUserIdAsync(user);
    var routeValues = new RouteValueDictionary()
    {
        ["userId"] = userId,
        ["code"] = code,
    };

    if (isChange)
    {
        // This is validated by the /confirmEmail endpoint on change.
        routeValues.Add("changedEmail", email);
    }

    var confirmEmailUrl = linkGenerator.GetUriByName(context, confirmEmailEndpointName, routeValues)
        ?? throw new NotSupportedException($"Could not find endpoint named '{confirmEmailEndpointName}'.");

    await emailSender.SendConfirmationLinkAsync(user, email, HtmlEncoder.Default.Encode(confirmEmailUrl));
}
```

### Describe the solution you'd like

I propose that the email confirmation process be handled entirely by the client, with the backend providing only a confirmation token and necessary metadata.

The client should be responsible for constructing the confirmation URL and managing the UI flow. This approach allows client side developers to easily modify the user interface and experience without needing backend changes. The backend would generate a confirmation token, which the client would use to build the confirmation URL and handle all user-facing steps of the confirmation process.

Additionally, the client would be able to send the confirmation email and any related messages, giving it full control over the email content and formatting. This would improve the separation of concerns between client side and backend and provide more flexibility in managing the email confirmation process.

```csharp
var clientOptions = userManager.Options.Client;
```

```csharp
// If ClientOptions are configured, use them to build the URL
if (clientOptions is not null)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(clientOptions.BaseUrl)
        || string.IsNullOrEmpty(clientOptions.EmailconfirmationRoute))
    {
        throw new InvalidOperationException("Client options are not correctly configured.");
    }

    var uriBuilder = new UriBuilder(clientOptions.BaseUrl)
    {
        Path = clientOptions.EmailconfirmationRoute
    };

    var queryParams = HttpUtility.ParseQueryString(uriBuilder.Query);

    queryParams["userId"] = userId;
    queryParams["code"] = code;

    // This is validated by the /confirmEmail endpoint on change.
    if (isChange)
    {
        queryParams["changedEmail"] = HttpUtility.UrlEncode(email);
    }

    uriBuilder.Query = queryParams.ToString();

    confirmEmailUrl = uriBuilder.ToString();
}
else
{
    var routeValues = new RouteValueDictionary()
    {
        ["userId"] = userId,
        ["code"] = code,
    };

    if (isChange)
    {
        // This is validated by the /confirmEmail endpoint on change.
        routeValues.Add("changedEmail", email);
    }

    confirmEmailUrl = linkGenerator.GetUriByName(context, confirmEmailEndpointName, routeValues)
        ?? throw new NotSupportedException($"Could not find endpoint named '{confirmEmailEndpointName}'.");
}
```

